text:
I appreciate the benefit of the doubt here, but I'm not sure how else this can be taken;

"Analysis can be found on-line about the cost of losing these people who harvest our crops, mow our lawns and do other labor that Americans won't do." 

It still seems pretty clear that he's advocating for gardeners. And it's still insulting.

In an example used by Sigmund Freud in The Interpretation of Dreams, a man accused by his neighbor of having returned a kettle in a damaged condition offered three arguments:
That he had returned the kettle undamaged;
That it was already damaged when he borrowed it;
That he had never borrowed it in the first place.

The bottom line is, under normal circumstances a region within a nation may not unilaterally secede from that nation. The separation must be negotiated in good faith between the separating region and the national government.

Note that term "good faith." It means that, at a minimum:

1) the seceding region must seek a clear, democratic mandate from its citizens to NEGOTIATE a secession;
2) constitutional procedures for secession (if any) must be followed by the region, or negotiated between the region and the national government;
3) the division of the social, political and physical assets within the region must be fair to both parties.

In the event that following 1) above the mother nation refuses to negotiate a secession in good faith, only then may a region legitimately undertake a unilateral secession. Nevertheless, doing so may well be considered an act of war on the part of the region. So the seceding region better be VERY certain it wants to go down that road.

